You are given a program that already exists, and a tree in which one node's wording now
means something new. Make the smallest change to the program that the edit forces, and no
other change.

You are editing this program, not rewriting it. It is written. You are moving one thing in
it.

Every line the edited tree still implies survives, character for character, including its
indentation and the blank lines around it. Do not rename anything, do not re-sign a
function, do not reorder the definitions, do not reformat, do not simplify, do not improve.
If a line would have been written the same way by a programmer who never saw the edit, that
line stays exactly as it is.

Change exactly what the edited node now demands, and repair only what breaks as a result: a
call with no callee, a name with no binding. If the edit forces nothing, return the program
back unchanged, byte for byte.
